<subSubSection id="6CD9657DFFB167315BE5CBB58D6221F6" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="247C36F6FFB167315BE5CBB58C26210E" blockId="4.[151,1437,153,935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315BE5CBB58FC120A2" bold="true" box="[199,408,728,755]" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">Species included:</emphasis>
Encompasses 
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315961CBB48CF320A2" authorityName="Trimen" authorityYear="1898" box="[579,682,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pyrgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delagoae">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315961CBB48CF320A2" box="[579,682,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">delagoae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315999CBB48D5320A2" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1875" box="[699,778,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pyrgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colotes">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315999CBB48D5320A2" box="[699,778,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">colotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB16731586FCBB48DF920A2" baseAuthorityName="Plotz" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[845,928,729,755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ernsta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dromus">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB16731586FCBB48DF920A2" box="[845,928,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">dromus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species groups, as they were defined by 
<bibRefCitation id="40524B07FFB167315EA0CBB48F7B2146" author="de Jong, R." pageId="4" pageNumber="186" pagination="23 - 146" refId="ref8814" refString="de Jong, R. (1978) Monograph of the genus Spialia Swinhoe (Lepidoptera, Hesperiidae). Tijdschrift voor entomologie, 121, 23 - 146." type="journal article" year="1978">de Jong (1978)</bibRefCitation>
. Full species list is given below. These are mostly African species, only three of which (
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315E24CB938B2C2146" authorityName="Druce" authorityYear="1875" box="[1286,1397,765,791]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Pyrgus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colotes">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315E24CB938B2C2146" box="[1286,1397,765,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">E. colotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315EA6CB938EA6216A" baseAuthorityName="Rebel" baseAuthorityYear="1899" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ernsta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mangana">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315EA6CB938EA6216A" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">E. mangana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315A1FCA4F8FC7216A" baseAuthorityName="Higgins" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[317,414,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Spialia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315A1FCA4F8FC7216A" box="[317,414,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) cross the Red Sea into the southern corner of the Arabian Peninsula, and one (
<taxonomicName id="E3C34D75FFB167315E39CA4F8B20216A" baseAuthorityName="Butler" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[1307,1401,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Spialia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="186" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zebra">
<emphasis id="16B7EAE4FFB167315E39CA4F8B20216A" box="[1307,1401,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">E. zebra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is recorded from the northwestern Himalayas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="247C36F6FFB167315BE5CA048D6221F6" blockId="4.[151,1437,153,935]" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">
The phylogenetic trees (
<figureCitation id="BCF82A73FFB167315AF5CA048C4121D2" box="[471,536,873,899]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1656,1681]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,179,1627]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,179,1629]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Phylogenetic trees of Carcharodina. The trees are constructed from nucleotide sequences of protein-coding regions from: a. nuclear genome; b. Z-chromosome; c. mitochondrial genome. Statistical significance values are shown by each node. d. COI barcode distance diagram is shown to emphasize on close relationships within Carcharodina. In panels a) and b), vertical green (yellow-shaded) line defines genera: each clade crossed by the line is a genus in our treatment; vertical thin gray (blue-shaded) line defines subgenera. Branches in Carcharodina are colored by genus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3697556" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3697556/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) suggest that this genus has split into two groups: one contains the 
<typeStatus id="FB788854FFB167315E36CA048B1D21D2" box="[1300,1348,873,899]" pageId="4" pageNumber="186">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus, and the other one is named here as a subgenus.
</paragraph>
